specs/wallaby/approved/glance/expose_tas.message:
Not sure if this is a good suggestion or not.  How about if the response is wrapped like this:

    {
        "messages": [
            {
                 "task": {
                     "id": etc, as above
            }
         ]
    }

This would future proof us for the situation where there are multiple messages for a single image, and they wouldn't all have to be task-based because "messages" is a list of JSON objects.

I was thinking that maybe the task response should be filtered, but my second thought is you are correct here, returning the full response provides enough information to really be able to troubleshoot a problem without exposing any system-sensitive info.  Plus, we've got documentation elsewhere (I think) that explains how to read a task-show response.

Just noticed that i missed a closing brace above.  What i mean is:

    {
        "messages": [
            {
                 "task": {
                     "id": etc, as above
                 }
            }
         ]
    }

I know that seems kind of overkill on the braces, but the idea is that we want the "messages" to be a list of JSON objects as opposed to being a named field of a JSON "messages" object.  Or maybe the best thing is to not worry about the future but just return a task object as in your original example.

Reading Dan's comments on PS3, I got the impression that he'd like to see all the non-expired tasks associated with this image in the response, not just the one in the os_glance_import_task property.  So maybe instead of the "No message" string, if there are no messages for this image, just return the response

  {
      "messages": []
  }

